<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-558-659  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 558 659.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Oct 29 1990 n293 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How to manage the recession.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Krass, Peter; Caldwell, Bruce; Schindler, Paul E., Jr.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many information system (IS) managers maintain that cost-cuttingand investment in new, more efficient systems are two ways tocombat a recession.andP;  Such an event would be an opportunity for ISmanagers to reassess their priorities.andP;  Switching to computerleasing and migrating systems from minicomputers to cheapermicrocomputer and workstation networks are two ways to cut costs.andO;Other suggestions are to make use of voice mail andteleconferencing instead of traveling.andP;  The use of opensystem-based networks can save money in the short term,predominantly by reducing duplication of systems and staff.andO;Outsourcing is one option many IS executives will consider,leading industry analysts to forecast 30 percent growth inoutsourced systems operations to $4.3 billion in 1991.andO;Information system budgets are usually sparse, leaving little roomfor cost-cutting in any dramatic form.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Economics of ComputingEconomics of InformationRecessionComputer IndustryInformation SystemsManagement StyleCost Reduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphphotograph.andO;Caption:   Survey of IS executives. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>